docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Facing a groundswell of public support for addressing systemic racism and excessive use of force in law enforcement, Democrats and Republicans have unveiled competing proposals to tackle the issues.

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane and Luke Broadwater

docs.abstract: This year late-night hosts took their shows remote during the pandemic, got serious about America’s biggest problems and prepared to say goodbye to President Trump (eventually).
docs.snippet: This year late-night hosts took their shows remote during the pandemic, got serious about America’s biggest problems and prepared to say goodbye to President Trump (eventually).
docs.lead_paragraph: Late-night television has been dominated by the foibles of President Trump for the last four years, but 2020 was perhaps the most daunting of all. Leading up to the November election, hosts tried to expand their focus to other candidates, but when it came to staying topical, Trump continued to dominate the news, especially once the coronavirus forced the country to more actively consider its leadership (or lack thereof) during the crisis.

headline.main: Best of Late Night in 2020: The Show Must Go Home

docs.abstract: Can bringing poems to the masses be an antidote to our toxic civic culture?
docs.snippet: Can bringing poems to the masses be an antidote to our toxic civic culture?
docs.lead_paragraph: One night in the summer of 2014, when she was teaching at the Middlebury Bread Loaf School of English in Vermont, Tracy K. Smith dreamed she was reading a poem printed on a wall. At first she thought it was by another poet, but as she reached the end, she realized it was her own. “If I wake up, I can get it,” she told herself.

headline.main: Tracy K. Smith, America’s Poet Laureate, Is a Woman With a Mission

docs.abstract: The best student comments from last week, and an invitation to join the conversation this week.
docs.snippet: The best student comments from last week, and an invitation to join the conversation this week.
docs.lead_paragraph: Most weeks we call out particular schools for being active participants in our writing forums, but this week we’d like to call out individual students. Maggie Yang and Brooke Myers, both from King of Prussia, Pa., commented on nearly every prompt we offered, and had interesting things to say about them all. Thank you for your contributions, Maggie and Brooke!

headline.main: Silence, Sneakers, Risk-Taking and Poetry: Our Favorite Student Comments of the Week
